{{Expand Korean|3·20 전산 대란|date=March 2013}}
{{Campaignbox Korean Cold War|state=expanded}}

On 20 March 2013, three [[South Korea]]n television stations and a bank suffered from frozen computer terminals in a suspected act of [[cyberwarfare]].<ref name=Guardian>Tania Branigan, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/20/south-korea-under-cyber-attack "South Korea on alert for cyber-attacks after major network goes down: Computer systems of banks and broadcasters are interrupted, with fingers immediately pointed at North Korea"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 20 March 2013.</ref>  ATMs and mobile payments were also affected. The South Korean communications watchdog raised their alert level on cyber-attacks to three on a scale of five. [[North Korea]] has been blamed for similar attacks in 2009 and 2011 and was suspected of launching this attack as well. South Korean officials linked the incident to a [[China|Chinese]] [[IP address]], which increased suspicion of [[North Korea]] as "[i]ntelligence experts believe that North Korea routinely uses Chinese computer addresses to hide its cyber-attacks." <ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=China IP address link to South Korea cyber-attack |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21873017 |newspaper=[[BBC]] |location= |date=21 March 2013 |access-date=September 12, 2016}}</ref>

[[Malware]] related to the attack is called "DarkSeoul" in the computer world and was first identified in 2012. The [[Financial Services Commission (South Korea)|Financial Services Commission of South Korea]] said that [[Shinhan Bank]] reported that its Internet banking servers had been temporarily blocked and that {{Interlanguage link multi|Jeju Bank|ko|3=제주은행}} and [[National Agricultural Cooperative Federation|NongHyup]] reported that operations at some of their branches had been paralyzed after computers were infected with viruses and their files erased. [[Woori Bank]] reported a hacking attack, but said it had suffered no damage. Computer shutdowns also hit companies including the [[Korean Broadcasting System]], [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]], and [[YTN]].<ref>Choe Sang-Hun, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/21/world/asia/south-korea-computer-network-crashes.html "Computer Networks in South Korea Are Paralyzed in Cyberattacks"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', 20 March 2013.</ref>

The South Korean government asserted a Pyongyang link in the March [[cyberattacks]], which has been denied by Pyongyang.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lee Minji |date=April 10, 2013 |title=(2nd LD) Gov't confirms Pyongyang link in March cyber attacks |url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2013/04/10/49/0401000000AEN20130410007352320F.HTML |newspaper=[[Yonhap News]] |location= |access-date=September 7, 2016}}</ref> A 50-year-old South Korean man identified as Mr. Kim is suspected to be involved in the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324136204578639540757695644|title=Seoul Suspects South Korean Tech Executive of Helping North in Cyberattacks|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|author=Jeyup S. Kwaak|date=July 31, 2013|accessdate=August 3, 2013}}</ref>

