{{rough translation|date=October 2017}} '''Augusto Marinoni''' (15 June 1911, [[Legnano]] - 31 December 1997)<ref>http://data.bnf.fr/12314465/augusto_marinoni/</ref> was professor of Filologia Romanza at the [[Catholic University of Milan]], a member of the [[Commissione Vinciana]] and the [[Academy of Lincei]]. He was an authority on the work of [[Leonardo da Vinci]].
==Early life== After completing his classical studies, he enrolled at ' Catholic University of the Sacred Heart , where he obtained in 1933 a degree in Literature and Philosophy [3] . Thanks to the lexicographic study, which began during the preparation of the thesis and continued later, Marinoni was able to identify the genesis, which is rooted in the Middle Ages , of the dictionary .
==Career== In 1936 he obtained a degree in Italian and Latin at Liceo Vittorio Veneto in Milan. In these years he began his studies on Leonardo da Vinci thanks to his knowledge in the lexiconic field. His work was initially focused on the eight thousand words contained in the Trivulzian Code , and the result of his studies was published by Giovanni Treccani while Marinoni was a prisoner of war ( 1943 - 1946 ) following his participation in the Second World War on the Front of the ' North Africa . He resumed his studies on Leonardo in 1952, on the occasion of the cinquecentennial of the birth of the genius vinciano. Thanks to the quality of her work, she received the applause of the members of a congress of Leonardo scholars that took place in Paris in the same year.
In 1958 he was appointed head of the Legnano high school . Two years later, thanks to the initiative of Marinoni, a high school in gymnasium was opened in Legnano in the high school. Also in 1958 he began collaborating with the Catholic University of Milan, where he taught romance philology until 1981 .
In 1968 he was appointed by President of the Republic Giuseppe Saragat , a member of the Ministerial Commission for the Manuscripts of Leonardo da Vinci . In this commission, Marinoni worked on the study, translation and description of winery codes preserved in Italy , namely the Trivulzian Code , the Atlantic Code and the Code on Bird Flight . Thanks to this immense work, Marinoni has published since the seventies all 14 volumes of the codes in question . In 1972, he began cooperation with Ladislao Reti on the transcription of the Madrid Codes , discovered in the Spanish capital. In 1974 he dealt with the dissemination of these codes, which were published in seven languages from MacGraw Hill.
Thanks to the quality of his work, Marinoni is considered the greatest expert on the philology of Leonardo da Vinci and the greatest expert of philosophical and scientific thought vinciano. Marinoni continued his studies on Leonardo da Vinci and continued his divulging activity, holding seminars in various European and world cities. Many companies, such as Philips and IBM , contributed to publishing their works and many cultural world institutions invited him to hold seminars and meetings. It is up to Marinoni to make the first CD-ROM with multimedia content on Leonardo da Vinci. He studied and published the contents of Code Forster in 1977, kept at the Victoria and Albert Museum in London , and the Ashburnham Code , guarded at the Institut de France in Paris. In 1982 he was appointed president of the Vinciana Collector 's Office in Milan, which still raises the greatest Italian and foreign scholars of Leonardo da Vinci . Among the awards he received, the Hammer "for excellence" , obtained from the University of Los Angeles in 1987 , should be remembered.
Augusto Marinoni also studied in depth the history of his city , Legnano, and his dialect . Augusto Marinoni is headquartered in the municipal library of Legnano, which is housed inside Villa Bernocchi .
==Selected publications== * ''Leonardo the Scientist''. McGraw-Hill, New York, 1980. (With [[Carlo Zammattio]] and [[Anna Maria Brizio]]) {{ISBN|0070727236}}
