{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}
'''Richard William Benet Salway''' is a senior lecturer in [[ancient history]] at [[University College London]].<ref>[http://iris.ucl.ac.uk/iris/browse/profile?upi=RWSAL86 IRIS] c.v. of Dr. Benet Salway</ref> His areas of speciality include Greek and Roman [[epigraphy]] and [[onomastics]], [[Roman law]], [[Roman Empire|Roman Imperial history]] and travel and geography in the [[Greco-Roman world|Graeco-Roman world]].

==Biography==

Salway attended [[The Queen's College, Oxford]], where he received his DPhil in 1995.

He was part-time tutor in Ancient History at [[St Anne's College, Oxford]] and part-time lecturer in Classics at the [[University of Reading]] 1993–94 and temporary lecturer in Ancient History at the [[University of Manchester]] 1994–95. He was then at [[University College London]] as post-doctoral research fellow on the [[British Academy]]/[[Arts and Humanities Research Council|Arts and Humanities Research Board]]-funded ''Projet Volterra: Law and Empire'' from 1995 to 1999. He was lecturer in Classics at the [[University of Nottingham]] 1999–2001 and moved back to [[University College London]] in 2001 as lecturer in Ancient History. In 2007 he was promoted to senior lecturer. In 2005 he became a director of ''Projet Volterra II: Law and the End of Empire''.<ref>{{cite web |author=Dr Simon Corcoran |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/history2/volterra/index.htm |title="Projet Volterra"; Introduction |publisher=UCL |date=14 July 2009 |accessdate=9 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100506075510/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/history2/volterra/index.htm |archivedate=6 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

Salway has held several other positions at [[University College London]]: elected non-professorial representative on the Academic Board 2002–05 and since 2006, elected non-professorial member of the Academic Committee 2004–05, elected non-professorial member of Council since 2006, non-professorial member of the Nominations Committee since 2007, member of the Academic Committee Sub-Committee on Probation since 2008, and non-professorial member of the Governance Committee since 2009.

He was also secretary of the British Epigraphy Society 1999–2004 and a member of the Council of the [[Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies]] 2002–05 and has been a member of the [[Institute of Classical Studies]] Library Committee since 2001 and Finance Committee since 2008.<ref>{{cite web|author=University College London |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/academic-manual/part-c/annexc8 |title=Members of UCL Council 2009–10 |publisher=UCL |accessdate=30 March 2010}}</ref>

==Gregorian Code discovery==
In 2010 the Volterra database was used by [[Simon Corcoran|Corcoran]] and Salway to identify previously unknown fragments of the [[Gregorian Code]]. The "Fragmenta Londiniensia" are seventeen pieces of parchment estimated to date from AD400, the document having been cut up and re-used as book-binding material. This is the first original evidence yet discovered of the Gregorian Codex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roger-pearse.com/weblog/?p=3466 |title=Lost Roman legal text found |first=Roger |last=Pearse |date=27 January 2010 |accessdate=27 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/News/Podcasts/Pages/lostromanlaw.aspx |title=Lost Roman law code discovered in London |publisher=[[Arts and Humanities Research Council]] |date=28 January 2010 |accessdate=28 January 2010 |format=Podcast |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100314192605/http://www.ahrc.ac.uk/News/Podcasts/Pages/lostromanlaw.aspx |archivedate=14 March 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=Jack2010>{{cite news |title=Cracking the codex: Long lost Roman legal document discovered |last=Jack |first=Malcolm |date=28 January 2010 |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/archaeology/news/cracking-the-codex-long-lost-roman-legal-document-discovered-1881769.html|quote=These fragments are the first direct evidence of the original version of the Gregorian Code. Our preliminary study confirms that it was the pioneer of a long tradition that has extended down into the modern era and it is ultimately from the title of this work, and its companion volume the Codex Hermogenianus, that we use the term 'code' in the sense of 'legal rulings'.}}</ref><ref name=Guardian2010>{{cite news |title=Experts identify scraps of lost Roman law text: Copy of the Gregorian Code, which was first drafted in AD300, had been chopped up and used to cover medieval book |last=Kennedy |first=Maev |date=28 January 2010 |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jan/28/gregorian-text-roman-law-found|quote=The fragments were bought by a private collector at a sale in London. After failing either to translate the script or identify the subject, he circulated photocopies which eventually reached Salway and Corcoran.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Rachel Kaufman |url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/02/100203-lost-codex-gregorianus-roman-law-book/ |title=Lost Roman Codex Fragments Found in Book Binding |publisher=National Geographic |date=10 February 2010 |accessdate=4 February 2010}}</ref>

