The '''Lupemban''' is the name given by [[archaeologist]]s to a central [[Africa]]n [[archaeological culture|culture]] which, though once thought to date between c. 30,000 and 12,000 BC, is now generally recognised to be far older (dates of c. 300,000 have been obtained from Twin Rivers, [[Zambia]] and Muguruk, [[Kenya]], respectively). The industry is characterised by the occurrence of bi-facially flaked [[lanceolate]] points. It has been postulated that Lupemban tools, being generally distributed within the modern day [[Congo Basin|Congo]] forest belt, may have been adapted to woodworking. The lanceolate points are commonly interpreted as being the surviving elements of composite spears.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com.kh/books?id=QYGwagdt9MQC&pg=PA234&lpg=PA234&dq=Lupemban+culture&source=bl&ots=cREr2Ux_Jf&sig=7_mWCfmO4V-EOPaIQoNrqom0cvA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiE_LXMyczRAhVTNpQKHX35Bdc4ChDoAQg6MAY#v=onepage&q=Lupemban%20culture&f=false |title=Kalambo Falls Prehistoric Site: Volume 3, The Earlier Cultures: Middle and ... - J. Desmond Clark, Julie Cormack, Susan Chin - Google Books |publisher=Google Books |date=  |author= |accessdate= January 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.antiquityofman.com/African_stone_tool_analyses_problems.pdf |title=Stone tools have been used as cognitive/chronological, cultural/ethnic, and functional/environmental indicators in African prehistory |publisher=Antiquityofman.com |date=  |author= |accessdate= January 19, 2017}}</ref>

Activity sites include: [[Kalambo Falls]] and [[Dundo]].

