'''Zahir al-Din Mar'ashi''' ({{lang-fa|ظهیرالدین مرعشی}}) was a [[Persian people|Persian]] commander, diplomat and historian. He is the author of several books on the history of [[Tabarestan]]. He was born in 812 AH (1412 AD) and died after 894 AH (1489 AD). He was from [[Marashis|Mar'ashi family]], an originally [[seyyed]] family in [[Tabarestan]] who dominated the region from the later 8th/14th century until the province's incorporation into [[Safavid Empire]] by [[Abbas I of Persia]] in 1005/1596. He stemmed from the main branch of Mar'ashis, that of Kamal al-Din ibn Kiwan al-Din. He owned states at Bazargah at Gilan and was employed by Sultan Muhammad II of Kar Kia line in Gilan and then by his son an successor Mirza Ali. He was sent to resolve militarily a succession dispute in adjacent Rustamdar and he led other expeditions, including an unsuccessful siege of Nur in 868/1463.<ref name="eoi">{{cite book|last1=Pellat|first1=prepared by a number of leading orientalists ; edited by ... H.A.R. Gibb, J.H. Kramers, E. Lévi-Provençal, J. Schacht, ... B. Lewis, Ch.|title=The encyclopaedia of Islam|date=1960|publisher=E.J. Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=9004127569|pages=393–394|edition=New|quote=}}</ref>
